xsy: Cay in wen zong tong zongtong 'am taypiyaw ka to'oya' tiSkobih ka SaSinSinraehoe' kina:at
english: President Tsai Ing-wen's Apology to the Indigenous Peoples on Behalf of the Government.

xsy: hini Sam'iyaeh o roSa' tinal'oemaeh ka kinSahpi:ihan ila. niya'om ray Sienfa: kina:at komSa' ka Sanpaw sapihin ila ka SaSinSinraehoe' karo:o'an.hini tinil'itol ka raro:o', boloe' ila kakhayza'an ka 'ima 'aewhay rino:o', 'am pakSekla' Sapang kamamalahang ka hini 'oemaeh 'isahini Sapang a toml 'ima rowaSek rini.saeboeh ka SinSinraehoe'. Sekla' ila ka 'inakhini'an howaw, kaysa'an yami 'am minsalaz ka kinaSkoraehan. yako 'iwana to'oya', 'am balong ka SinSinrahoe' saeboeh, 'aring to'oya' kaS'abo' tabin 'isahini pinatawaw 'okay paylal'oz, 'omahoiS ila! hini Sopat kin kabhoel o hayza'ila tinal'oemaeh, 'inimon 'akoey ka kinhopay ki 'ima wawili' ka kinalahang, yako 'iwan ila ka 'ayporong, rini yako 'am komSa'ila: 'omahoiS ila!
english: On this day 22 years ago, the term "shanbao" (mountain people) in the Additional Articles of our Constitution was replaced with the proper name: "indigenous people." This correction not only did away with a discriminatory term, but also highlighted the status of indigenous peoples as Taiwan's "original owners." From this basis, today, we are taking another step forward. To all indigenous peoples of Taiwan: On behalf of the government, I express to you our deepest apology. For the four centuries of pain and mistreatment you have endured, I apologize to you on behalf of the government.

xsy: ya:o Sekla', kanmita' hani saeboeh ma' 'ima hayza a ka 'aroma' komSa'ay! kayzaeh! hini kapowa'en Sipnabih. kaysa'an ma'an 'ima Sil'i: kapayaka:i' howawkoSa'en 'am boloe' ka 'imahoiS ray hin'az'azem. kakhayza'an noka saeboeh kinhopayan, nakhara' ila komSa hini kinhopay niya'om nonak pinanra:anan, kaysa'an yami miriri:i' rini, 'ita' tatalam sapih ila saeboeh ka hin'az'azem konaeh.
english: I know that even now, there are some around us who see no need to apologize. But that is the most important reason why I am representing the government to issue this apology today. To see what was unfair in the past as a matter of course, or to treat the pain of other ethnic peoples as an unavoidable part of human development, this is the first mindset that we, standing here today, resolve to change and overturn.

xsy: yako tapanabih 'inimon, 'ampowa' tiSkobihkoSa'en ka hini SaSinSinraehoe' saboeh. hini 'oemaeh koSa'en taywan, ray 'ima Sahpi:ih ilaSopat kinkabhoel tinal'oemaeh hayza' ila ka ma'iaeh rini 'ima rowaSek. 'a'aringan 'ima rowaSek rini mae'iyaeh, lasiya hayza ni nonak ka kapayaka:i', kaspengan,hayza koSa'en ka kin rowaSekan nasiya nonak. bi:il ila,mowa:i' ka Say kabih no wasal ma'iyaeh kaShowih ila ka hini 'oemaeh.
english: Let me put in simple terms why we are apologizing to the indigenous peoples. Four hundred years ago, there were already people living in Taiwan. These first inhabitants lived their lives and had their own languages, cultures, customs, and domains. But then, without their consent, another group of people arrived on these shores, and in the course of history, took everything from the first inhabitants who, on the land they have known most intimately, became displaced, foreign, non-mainstream, and marginalized.

xsy: kakhayza'an wa:i'in ila noka 'ima haba:an ma'iyaeh, mowa:i' 'ana kano' paraylis ila. Sapang 'ima minSa'la' rowaSek rini ka ma'iyaeh, paka'aroma'en, nakhara' 'aehae' taew'an Sohowihin ka ma'iyaeh ila. 'aehae' Sinraehoe' 'am min'itol, koza' ma' 'ima hayza'a pakhopay koSa'en moyo kaSaSinSinraehoe', 'oka' ila niya'om So: 'okay hapa:i: Sa' hini mina 'ima ra:am malahang ka ma'iyaeh ka to'oya', hini kakhayza'an 'inak'ino'ana howaw ma' Sipnabih saeboeh. 'isa:, hini 'ima Sil'i: howaw, ka to'oya' minaho'az'azem a tomal, hini howaw 'isahini kataka'ino'on, 'isa: kayasa'an 'ampowa' ya:o miriri:i' rini.
english: The success of one ethnic people can be built on the suffering of another. Unless we deny that we are a country of justice, we must face up to this history. We must tell the truth. And then, most importantly, the government must genuinely reflect on this past. This is why I stand here today.

xsy: hayza' 'aehae' kina:at koSa'en"taywan ka pinara:anan howaw." ha:aw kina:at komSa' (taywan kakhayza'an 'oka' ka kina:at, helan tomay'alay, o hizenSe' ila ko'oemaeh, 'isa: 'ima botoe' ka bekeS to'oya'mowa:i' malahang). hini ma' 'in noka moto: a nonak ka kinita' ki hin'az'azem. SaSinSinaraehoe', rawSek rini koza' ila kin honaehnge: ka tina'oemaeh, lasiya hayza' ni nonak ka 'ima tomal ka kaspengan, SipataSilotor ka minahael o minahael. 'oka' ila, yami paspeng nanaw tani noka kin haeba:an ka kinita' koma:at ka hini howaw. tani hini yako 'iwana to'oya' yako 'am tiSkobih ka SaSinSinraehoe' komSa' 'omaho:iS ila.
english: There is a book called "The General History of Taiwan" published in 1920. In its foreword are these words: "Taiwan had no history. The Dutch pioneered it, the Koxinga Kingdom built it, and the Qing Empire managed it." This is a typical Han view of history. The truth is that indigenous peoples have been here for thousands of years, with rich culture and wisdom that have been passed down through generations. But we only know to write history from the perspective of the dominant. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

xsy: helan ki zenSe' to'oya' kakhayza'an tomi'lihlih ka panaeh, tombok, raylis ka kaehaew. somapih ila ka'ima botoe' ka bekeS to'oya', hingha' 'oka' ka kinalahang, komonre're' ka SaSinSinraehoe'. mowa:i' ila ka ripon, 'isa: 'a'apolen ila Say'isahini ki Saykabih no wasal, paknonaken ila ka kakrowaSekan, tabin mowa:i' kababoy 'isa: nasiya ka SaSinSinraehoe' Sa' pahamoto:on ila. Sopat kinkabhoel ila tinal'omaeh, 'aehae " aehae " ima mowa:i' rini taywan to'oya', lasiya 'ano noka wa'is raylis ka 'oemaeh, pa'aewhay ka 'ima kin kayzaeh ka kin'i'iyaeh. 'isa: yako 'am komSa' 'omaho:iS ila saeboeh.
english: The Dutch and the Koxinga Kingdom massacred and exploited the Pingpu ethnic group. The Qing Empire presided over bloody confrontations and suppression. Colonial Japan put in place comprehensive savage policies. And the post- war ROC government undertook assimilation policies. For 400 years, every regime that has come to Taiwan has brutally violated the rights of indigenous peoples through armed invasion and land seizure. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

xsy: SaSinSinraehoe' ray 'asang tanikaspengan, tanikintatini'an ka kinSekla'an 'i'iyaeh. 'oka' ila, 'isahini komita' ila kapinanra:anan, noka SaSinSinraehoe' 'oka' ila ninonak ka sinpengan, 'oka' ila kakalahang hi nonak. kakhayza'an kintatini'an sipengan 'oka' ila. noka SinSinraehoe' kaspengan haysani noka to'oya' ma' 'okay paka:i'i. 'isa: yako 'am komSa' 'omahoiS ila saeboeh.
english: Indigenous peoples maintain tribal order according to traditional customs, and ecological balance according to traditional wisdom. But in the process of modern state-building, indigenous peoples lost the right to steer their own course and govern their own affairs. The fabric of traditional societies was torn apart, and the collective rights of peoples were not recognized. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

xsy: hini SaSinSinraehoe' hayza' saeboeh nasiya nonak kapayaka:i', mowa:i'ka ripon pahariponen ila. ray 1945 tinal'oemaeh, mowa:i' ila ka baboy hingha " emlet Si'alnoSaySiyat, 'isa: noka SaySiyat ka:i' hawka' ila saeboeh. hingha' haeba:an panah ma " oka' ila 'inonaka kapayaka:i'. 'inaykakhayza'an ka to'oya', 'okay kalahang a tomal ka kaspengan noka SaSinSinraehoe', 'isa: yako 'am komSa' 'omaho:iS ila saeboeh.
english: Indigenous peoples had their own languages. However, with Japanese rule aiming to assimilate and turn all into imperial subjects, and with the ROC government banning tribal languages after 1945, indigenous peoples' languages suffered great losses. Most Pingpu languages have disappeared. Successive governments have been negligent in the protection of indigenous cultures. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

xsy: kakhayza'an, "yamiSinraehoe'"'inokik'a'a:ih 'aSkanen ka minsapae' noka 'ayporong. Say "lan'i:" mae'iyaeh narmeS ka pina'aewhay ka 'oemaeh. 'isa: yako 'am komSa' 'imahoiS ila "yamiSinraehoe'"
english: Without the knowledge of the Yami tribe, the government stored nuclear waste on Orchid Island. Tribe members on the island had to suffer the negative consequences. For this, I apologize to the Yami people on behalf of the government.

xsy: 'aring mowa:i' ila ka Say kabih no wasal, 'ima rowaSek ray kaheheban papa:awan ka panaeh minSa'la' pa'aewhayen. kakhayza'an kamamalahang ka panaeh to'oya' pak'oka'en ila nasiya raro:o'. 'isa: yako 'am komSa' 'omaho:iS ila ka panaeh.
english: Ever since outsiders began arriving in Taiwan, the Pingpu ethnic group on the western plains have born the brunt of the impact. One ruling power after another eroded the individual and collective identities of the Pingpu ethnic group. For this, I apologize to the Pingpu ethnic group on behalf of the government.

xsy: 'am pahinrowa' ila, to'oya' 'ina tiSkobaeoeh noka SaSinSinraehoe' ka Sinina'. to'oya' 'ina Somiwa', ma' hayza' matawaw ila. tabinhaysani niya'om hayza' ila ka "nom malahang ka SaSinSinraehoe' kina:at," 'oka' ila, hini kina:at,noka to'oya' 'ae'tor ka pinatawaw. 'isa: yako 'am komSa' 'omahowiS ila ka SaSinSinraehoe'.
english: After the democratic transition, the country began to respond to the appeals of indigenous movements. The government made certain promises and efforts. Today, we have an Indigenous Peoples Basic Law that is quite advanced. However, government agencies have not given sufficient weight to this law. Our actions have not been fast enough, comprehensive enough or sound enough. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

xsy: taywan kinoSa' "'ima'akoy ka kaspeng noka SaSinSinraehoe'"to'oya'. 'oka' ila, tabin haysani, noka to'ya' pinatawaw no SaSinSinraehoe' 'okik lal'oz nanaw, kita'en ki wasal ka kin'i'iyaeh ma' papawaS a tomalan. 'isahini, hayza' nahan kama Sa'i:i' ka SaSinSinraehoe'. noka to'oya' haysiya 'okik lal'oz ka kinalahang pakhopay ka kin'i'iyaeh. 'isa: yako 'am komSa' 'imahoiS ila ka. SaSinSinraehoe'
english: Taiwan is known as a culturally diverse society. But even today, indicators on health, education, economic livelihood, political participation and more still show gaps between indigenous and non- indigenous peoples. Meanwhile, stereotypes and even discrimination against indigenous peoples have not gone away. The government has not done enough, so indigenous peoples have suffered pain and frustration unknown to other ethnic peoples. For this, I apologize to the indigenous peoples on behalf of the government.

xsy: to'oya " oki kakreng a tomal, sa'sa'ih ka to'oya' ma' 'ana sowiti' 'okay hohoro: hayza' nahan 'inokay patawawi,isa: pakhopay ila ka saeboeh tabin 'isahini. 'omahowiS ila sa'iwaz. kasa'an tiSkobih nakhara' ma'ngel ila sowiti', kayzaeh, 'isa: niya'om hayza ila ka'iya'alayan. yako 'okay koSa' Sopat kinkaboehoel tinal'oemaeh tini'li'lihan noka hini 'aehae' kakina:at 'aehae' ka:i' tiniSkobih 'am pawka' ka 'ima 'aewhay ka hina'azem. 'oka' ila, yako ma' pa'alo' kas'an tiniSkobih,hini noka to'oya' kinalahaeng saeboeh kakayzaehan kaya'alayan.
english: Our efforts have fallen short, and succeeding generations have been blind to this inadequacy. Because of this, your hardship has continued to this day. For this we are truly sorry. Today's apology is long overdue, but it is a beginning. I do not expect any one speech or phrase of apology to wipe away four centuries of pain and suffering by the indigenous peoples. But I do hope with all my heart that today's apology will set this country and all its people on the path towards reconciliation.

xsy: 'isahini yako 'am pa'alo 'aehae' ka:i', 'am pakra:am Sa' mowa:i' rini koSa'en kano'. noka Saypapa:aS hayza' kapayaka:i' koSa'en "kapakSekla'," ma' koSa'en Balay, o "papaskayzaeh" koSa'en Sblay, hini roSa' koSa'en Sapang kakaykayzaehan, hayza' ila mita' ka kinSekla' pinanra:an, tiniSkobih mita' ma' 'am hayza' ka kalokngoran.
english: Please allow me to shed light on this occasion with a piece of indigenous wisdom. In the Atayal language, truth is called "Balay," and reconciliation is called "Sbalay," so you simply add an "S" sound to "Balay." Truth and reconciliation are in fact two related concepts. In other words, only by facing the truth sincerely can reconciliation be attained.

xsy: noka SaSinSinraehoe' ka kaspengan, So: hayza ma'iyaeh mowa:i' pakonkonaeh ka Say 'asang, 'am haha:ong a, noka tatini' 'alotoron. raroton 'okay rae'seb makSa', minSa'la' papnabihhini ka howaw minay'ino', sizaeh haehae:ong 'isa: rae'seb ila, 'ima 'aewhay howaw pakSaehpi:ihin ila. hini koSa'en Sbalay.
english: In indigenous cultures, when a tribe member has offended another and intends to reconcile, an elder brings together the offender and the offended - not to produce a direct apology, but to allow each side to frankly share their inner journeys. When this truth-telling concludes, the elder calls for everyone to drink together, so that what is past is truly past. This is "Sbalay."

xsy: yako ma'az'azem kaysa'an rini, ma' 'iwan to'ya' ki SaSinSinraehoe' tatiSkosasbong koSa'en Sbalay. 'inkakhayza'an noka to'oya' 'ima 'okik paylaz'oz howaw ma'an ka papnabih pakSekla' ka saeboeh. SinSinraehoe'. 'insa'an moyo SinSinraehoe' ma' 'am hayza' ka kapnabih. yako 'am 'okay koSa' moyo 'isahini' Siwa' ila 'inimaman. 'oka' ila, yako tapa'alo' 'imoyo pak'es'es ka hin'az'azem no mayhal, 'ita' 'izi' ila i kaShal nahan ka 'ima 'aewhay ra:an, hini to'oya', tabin mayhael kaSahoero:on 'ima tilka:an ra:an.
english: I hope today's occasion can be a "Sbalay" between the government and the indigenous peoples. I have spoken of past mistakes and truths the best I can, with nothing held back. In a moment, our indigenous friends will speak. I do not dare ask you to forgive, here and now. But I sincerely ask you to sustain the hope that past wrongs will not be repeated, and that one day, this country can see true reconciliation.

xsy: kaysa'an 'imatomay'alay nanaw, 'am hiya' nom homawar ka hini howaw, 'okik moyo SaSinSinraehoe' ki panaeh, hini 'in niya'om a to'oya' ka howaw. yako ra:am, noka ngabas nanaw tiSkobih 'okay paka:i' i, So: Sahoero:on ila hini noka to'oya' ka pinatawawan no SaSinSinraehoeh, hini 'isa:a' Sapang 'am pawka' noka SaSinSinraehoeh 'ima 'omahowiS hin'az'azem.
english: Today is only a beginning. The duty for reconciliation lies not with the indigenous peoples and the Pingpu ethnic group, but with the government. I know that words of apology alone are not enough. What we actually do for the indigenous peoples will decide whether reconciliation succeeds or stumbles.

xsy: yako rini 'am pakSekla'ka saeboeh, kawna'ayporong 'am maSkan koSa'en ka"kakhayza' SaSinSinraehoeh pinak'aehayan nom pahinrowa' kapatawawan." yako 'ayporong nom malroton ka SaSinSinraehoeh, tapahinrowa' ka hini kakhayza'an pinak'aehayan howaw, ki moyo saeboeh ma'onhal matawaw, ma' 'am pakhingha' ka Sina:eng mita', mahrahrang ka hini 'inokato'oya'a mayhal ka panra:anan.
english: Therefore, I am here to announce that we are setting up an Indigenous Historical Justice and Transitional Justice Commission under the Presidential Office. As the head of state, I will serve as convener and work hand in hand with tribal representatives to pursue historical justice. We will also discuss, on the basis of equality, the future policy direction of this country.

xsy: yako 'am manabih, hini noka 'ayporong ka kapatawawan, Sapang 'ima Sil'i: ka kinita','isa: 'ayporong ki SaSinSinraehoe' hingha' ka Sina:eng. kakoSinraehoe' 'inaSkan nom ma:ngbas,tani kakoSinraehoe' kaspenganra:an matawaw. hini kapatawawen'am tani SaSinSinraehoe' pina tatinola' pinahrahrangan, kayzaeh noka SaSinSinraehoe' ka hin'az'azem ma' Sekla'en noka to'oya'.
english: I want to stress that this commission places the greatest importance on equality between the country and the indigenous peoples. The election of tribal representatives, including for the Pingpu ethnic group, will take as basis the consensus of peoples and tribes. This commission will serve as a mechanism for collective decision-making by indigenous peoples, and will ensure that the voices of tribe members find true expression.

xsy: 'oka' ila o, yako ma' 'am mayaka:i' ka kamasempeng kapatawaw to'oya' paSo:piza' 'ilaS kalhal raroton mahrahrang ka "nom malahaeng ka SaSinSinraehoe' kin'i'iyaeh ka kina:at." ray hini kapatawawan'izo' ka pinaraehraengan hingha' saboeh kahin'az'azem, mayhal to'oya' 'am ray 'ima 'ibabawaw ka'aiyalaho:an papnabih ka howaw, ka papnabih howaw hayza'koSa'en'am papahoro: 'inkakhayza'an ka kintatini'an, SaSinSinraehoe' nonak ' malahang hi nonak, 'am pakhingha' hayza' ka katikaehaewan, kaSika:atan okaspengan, nom kataSilotoran, kapakiyakalihaehan noka saeboeh, ki nom malahang 'ima bo:waw ray rahoeran, hini saeboeh kapatawaw mita'.
english: In addition, I will request that our Executive Yuan convene regularly the Indigenous Peoples Basic Law Promotion Committee, and use the Yuan's authority to coordinate and handle matters related to any consensus reached by the above-mentioned commission. These matters include the following: to retrieve historical memories, to promote indigenous self-government, to seek fair economic development, to ensure continuation of culture and education, to safeguard indigenous health, and to protect the rights of urban indigenous peoples, etc.

xsy: haysani kina:at kaspengan noka to'ya' ki SaSinSinraehoe' kaspengan, 'okik hingha' a tomalan, yami 'isa: 'am tomil'itol"nokaSaSinSinraehoe' pinpapoe'oe kaSarolan kina:at kapatawawan"paspeng ka hini kapatawawan, kayzaeh mayhal So: kaspengan'okik hingha' ma' hayza nom pa'inrowa' ka howaw.
english: Where modern laws and indigenous traditional cultures are at odds, we will set up an Indigenous Legal Service Center with a high degree of cultural sensitivity, to reduce through institutional design the growing clashes between indigenous customs and modern laws.

xsy: yami ma' tomrong ka kama matawaw, 'am'amoeh patawaw, noka SaSinSinraehoe' ka kaspengan, kahinra:i'an, hayza ma'iyaeh kan nonak 'oemaeh mari' ka kano', ma' hayza rakepen,hayza Sowabosen. 'inakhini'an yami ma' ma'za'zem 'am nak'ino' matawaw.
english: I will ask the relevant agencies to immediately pull together cases in which indigenous community members have been indicted or sentenced for hunting, where the hunting was done in accordance with traditional customs, on traditional lands, and for non-transactional needs, and where the animals hunted were not protected by conservation laws. For such cases we will deliberate solutions.

xsy: noka to'oya' ka 'ima min'aewhayan sapae' SiSaroton ray lan'i:, yako ma' 'am pa'alo' ka kama matawaw 'am'amoeh patawaw, 'az'azem karotonen rayno' kayzaeh. So: 'i'ini' nanaw i: tilkoraehi, ma' pakhaysiya ka kabe:ayan.
english: I will also direct relevant agencies to present an investigative report on the decision-making process of nuclear waste storage on Orchid Island. Before finding a permanent solution for the nuclear waste, we will provide the Yami tribe appropriate compensation.

xsy: rini hingha', tani panaeh 'am tomil'itol ka raro:o' nasiya, yami 'am minSa'la' ray 9 ilaS 30 hahila:, 'am komita' ka kaspengan kina:at, kayzaeh minobih nom tomil'itol nahaen ka raro:o' nopanaeh.
english: At the same time, under the principle of respecting the Pingpu ethnic group's self- identity, and recognizing their identity, we will examine relevant laws before September 30 of this year, so that Pingpu ethnic group identity will receive the rights and status it deserves.

xsy: ray kaysa'an tinal'oemaeh 11 ilaS 1 hahila:, yami 'am tomay'alay matawaw, 'am pakSekla' ka saboeh noka SaSinSinrehoe' kahinra:i'an 'omaeh. koSa'en hito' nak mae'iyaeh ka kaspengan, niya'om Sikontotol kakoway manra:an ila. mayhal, 'iyakina: nonak malahang hi nonak, hini hi'az'azem maySoSowaw kapinanra:an ma' 'am kalokngor. yami ma' 'am 'omam'amoeh matawaw noka SaSinSinraehoe' kinSobaeh noka"SaSinSinraehoe' nonak malahang hi nonak kina:at,""nokaSaSinSinraeh oe " oemaeh ki wasal kina:at," "nom komontotol SaSinSinraehoe' kapayaka:i' kina:at"hini saeboeh, kaSateren raykamatomil'itol ka kaspengan to'oya' paspeng hi lasiya.
english: On November 1 of this year, we will begin to delineate and announce indigenous traditional territories and lands. The system of tribal public corporation is already in place. In the future, the ideals of indigenous self-government will be realized step by step. We will step up the pace and submit for legislative deliberation three laws of great importance to indigenous peoples: the Indigenous Peoples Self-Government Law, the Indigenous Peoples Land and Sea Areas Law, and the Indigenous Languages Development Law.

xsy: yako 'am ma'alo' ka SaSinSinraehoe', moyo patinekla' ila ka saeboeh ma'iyaeh, noka 'ae'ay Sinarak ka rape: ki 'ima kintatini'an kaspengan, hayza' saboeh nasiya ka kinSobaehan, hini ma' be:ay a tomal ka raro:o'hi lasiya.
english: I want to thank all of our indigenous friends. You remind everyone in this country that there is irreplaceable value in the land we tread on and the traditions we inherit. This value deserves dignity.

xsy: mayhal, 'ita' 'amtani sinpengan komontotol. mita' minahael, minahael o minahaelki Say hini taywan ka SaSinSinraehoe', 'am 'okay pawka' ila kapayaka:i' ninonak, 'am 'okay pawka' ila ka hi'az'azem ninonak, 'am'okay ngowip kakinSekla'an nonak ma' 'am 'okay papa:waS ki kaspengan, 'am 'okay paktoliyab ila hi nonak ray hini 'oemaeh babaw.
english: In the future, we will push for policies to ensure that succeeding generations of indigenous tribes and all ethnic peoples in Taiwan never lose their languages and memories, that they are never separated from their cultural traditions, and that never again are they lost in a land of their own.

xsy: yako pa:'alo' ta kilwa'is saeboeh, taSekla'mita' kakinSekla'an,Sekla' ka hini 'oemaeh ma' Sekla' 'inokik hingha' ka SinSinraehoe' ka kaspengan.. tani pinahrahrangan hinawar ra:an, honsasaboeh rini ray rape: kakaykayzaehan, ma' 'am mowa:i' ila ka'ima SaSo' o tilka:an taywan.
english: I call upon our entire society to come together and get to know our history, get to know our land, and get to know the cultures of our many ethnic peoples. Let us work towards reconciliation, a shared existence and shared prosperity, and a new future for Taiwan.

xsy: yako 'am pa:'alo' ka saeboeh, nak kaysa'an hini 'aehae' hahila:, 'ita' tapa'onhal tapatawaw ka hini mita' kakrowaSekan 'oemaeh, pak sa'owaz 'oka' ka kin hahili'an, 'oka' ka kakSa'i:i'an noka saeboeh.
english: I call upon all citizens to seize the opportunities offered by this day - to join together, work hard, and build a country of justice, a country of true diversity and equality.

xsy: ka:i' nom kayni' ray taywan nantaw ka ka:i' noka kano' Sinrahoe'?
english: What word class are negators in Formosan languages?

english: Topics vs. subjects in Formosan languages

english: A four-way distance contrast in Takbanuaz Bunun deixis

english: Book Launch: Handbook of Formosan Languages

english: The mystery of Atayalic /x/: An exploration of Its origin

xsy: kamatortoroe' kaysa'an 'am maraS 'inimon rima' ray pinatiyay.
english: I will take you to the fields.

xsy: yami 'am rima' manibih ay ka ra:i'?
english: Are we going to loosen the soil?
Teacher will take us to the riverside.
Teacher will take us to the mountains today.
Are we going to the riverside today?
No, our teacher is going to take us to the mountains.
Are we going to the mountains today?
No, we are going to the fields.

xsy: kamatortoroe', 'ita' ray ba:la' 'am komita' ka kano'?
english: Teacher, what are we going to see at the riverside?
We are going to see dragonflies.

xsy: kamatortoroe', 'ita' rima' ray koko:ol 'am komita' ka kano'?
english: Teacher, what are we going to see in the mountains?
We are going to see butterflies.
What are we going to do in the fields?

xsy: 'ita' 'am rima' ray pinatiyayan komita' mita' pinamowa' ka basaeh, 'iya'azem ka 'ae'aewzaeh ki walwalo' o.
english: We are going to see the corn we grow in the fields, but you need to be aware of the ants and bees.
Teacher, are we going to swim in the river?
No, we are going to see dragonflies.

xsy: kamatortoroe' 'ita' 'am rima' ray pinatiyayan mamowa' ka por'oe' ay?
english: Teacher, are we going to grow some vegetables in the fields?
We are going to loosen the soil today.

xsy: yako kaysa'an ila komita' ka 'ima 'i'iyaeh ka 'ayloSay.
english: Today is the first time I see real living dragonflies.

xsy: hiza hayza' ka papa:o' mam homayhayap.
wa! ya:o minowa' ka papa:o', kayzaeh a tomal kita'en
english: Yeh! Wow! I love butterflies. They are very beautiful.
Those are not butterflies. They are bees.
Come here and take a look. Don't go too far!
Got it, we won't go anywhere too far.
Don't run and walk slowly lest you fall down.
I want to see them right away.
How do you go to the block-house?

xsy: yako seme:ez ka kapapama'an rima' ray hataS.

english: How does he go to the hospital?
How do you go to Penghu?

xsy: yako papama' ka palono' rima' ray kabih no wasal.
english: I go to Penghu by boat.

xsy: yako papama' ka ziyae'yon lobih ray taew'an.
mowi' papama' ka kano' rima' ray kakiSka:atan?
english: How does mowi' go to school?

xsy: mowi' papama' ka kalihapoyan rima' ray kakiSka:atan.
'ataw papama' ka kano' rima' ray kiyokay?
'ataw papama' ka zitinSiya' rima' ray kiyokay.
So'o papama' ka ziyae'yon ay rima' kiSka:at?
english: Do you go to school by MRT?

xsy: 'oka', ya:o papama' ka baSe' rima' kiSka:at.
english: No, I go to school by bus.

xsy: So'o papama' ka zitinSiya' ay rima' kiSka:at?
english: Do you go to school by bicycle?

xsy: 'ihi' yako papama' ka zitinSiya' rima' kiSka:at.
english: Yes, I go to school by bicycle.

xsy: So'o papama' ka kawti' ay rima' ray taka:o'?
english: Do you go to Kaohsiung by High Speed Rail?

xsy: 'ihi', yako papama' ka kawti' rima' ray taka:o'
english: Yes, I go to Kaohsiung by High Speed Rail.

xsy: So'o rima' ray taytong papama' ka kalihapoyan a hikoki'?
english: Are you going to Taitung by train or by plane?

xsy: yako papama' ka hikoki', hikoki' 'alikaeh no kalihapoyan.
english: I will take the plane because it is faster than the train.

xsy: So'o rima' ray kiyokay papama' ka baSe' a seme:ez ka kapapama'an?
english: Are you going to drive to the church or take the bus?

xsy: yako seme:ez ka kapapama'an rima' kiyokay, nonak seme:ez kayzaeh no papama' ka baSe'.
english: I will drive to the church because it is more convenient than the bus.
Is the market close to your house?

xsy: 'oka', yako seme:ez ka 'otobay rima' ray katibae:iwan.
english: No, it is not, so I always ride the motorcycle to the market.

xsy: kaSateran ka kina:at 'al'alihan ay ki kakiSka:atan?
english: Is the post office close to the school?
Yes, it is within walking distance.

xsy: kasi'aelan 'al'alihan ay ki ka'ayna:a'an ka kapapama'an?
english: Is the restaurant close to the station?

xsy: kaSlatar ray ka'ayna:a'an manra:an haseb Sinepe: 'isa:a' ma' potngor ila.
english: It only takes five minutes after you walk out of the station.
I would like to visit you.

xsy: yako kaysa'an hayza' ka howaw 'okik ray taew'an. So: 'inowan ila.
english: I am out today. How about another day?

xsy: So'o rim'aen honasamez ay? yako hila:an taSa' kita' 'iSo'on.
english: Then, are you available tomorrow? I'll visit you tomorrow afternoon.
Sure, I will wait for you at home.

xsy: yako kayzaeh ay 'omalingo' niSo' ka payaka:i'?
english: Would you mind if I do the voice recording?
Would you mind if I do the video recording?

xsy: yako 'okik kayzaeh kita'en, ma'an saksaka: ma' 'okay tal'izaeh i, 'izi' la.
english: No, I am plain and the warehouse hasn't been tidied up yet.
Then I will just take photos.
Thank you for accepting the interview.
You are welcome. What would you like to know?
What do you do when you are young?

xsy: kakhayza'an yako kinSat, 'isahini yako patae'aes ila.
english: I was a police officer but I am retired now.
Then, are you working at the moment?

xsy: korkoring niSo' ma' rowaSek ray 'asang ay?
english: Do your kids live in the tribe too?
No, my kids are all living in the city.
Then, do you live by yourself?

xsy: ya:o hayza' Sompan 'aehae' ka 'aehoe' ki 'aehae' kabkabaehae:, lasiya ma' 'aehae' taew'an ma'an.
english: I also keep a dog and a bird. They are my family.

xsy: ya:o ma' hayza' Sompan 'aehae' ka ngiyaw, hayza' ka kaSinpanan kayzaeh hayza' ka kapatawawen.
english: I have a cat too. I won't get bored with the company of my pet.

xsy: yako 'am somingozaw 'iSo'on noka kama'alep ka katiyawan.
english: I would like to ask you about the taboos of hunting.

xsy: yako 'okik Sekla' a tomal ka hini howaw, So: yako ra:am ma' 'am pakSekla' 'iSo'on.
english: I don't know much about that, but I will tell you everything I know.

xsy: nimon nom 'omalep ka kakrangi'an hayza' ay kano' katiyawan?
english: Do you have any taboos about hunting weapons?

xsy: niya'om nom 'omalep ka kakrangi'an, minkoringan 'aewhay pon'a:iS.
english: Our hunting weapons are untouchable to women.
Then, can women go hunting together?
No, women cannot go hunting either.

xsy: kalih, ray taew'an 'oka' ila ka pinobae:aeh, So'o Sa'ila bae:iw ka pinobae:aeh.
english: kalih, our home is out of rice wine, please go and buy some.

xsy: ray katalekan hayza' 'aehae' naehan binbiniSitan ka pinobae:aeh, So: 'okay bae:iw ma' kayzaeh la!
english: There is still one bottle left in the kitchen, so there is no need to buy one!

xsy: 'aehae' nanaw 'okik lal'oz, Sa'ila bae:iw roSa' binbiniSitan naehan.
english: One bottle is not enough for me, go and buy two more back.

xsy: yako 'am bae:iw ka pinobae:aeh, nimon hayza' ay?
english: I am looking for rice wine. Do you have any rice wine?
Yes! How many bottles do you need?

xsy: yako 'am bae:iw roSa' binbiniSitan ka pinobae:aeh, ki 'aehae' pinotoy ka Si'Si'.
english: I want two bottles and a pack of rice.

xsy: Si'Si' hini, niSo' 'am kano' naehan kabae:iwen?
english: Here is the rice, what else do you need?

xsy: yako 'am bae:iw ka 'oesizo:, nimon hayza' ay?
english: I want some eggs too, do you have some?
I want to buy some clothes.
What kind of clothes do you like?
I want to buy the clothes with short sleeves.

xsy: hini 'aehae' 'ima ngangilaehan ka kayba:en kayzaeh ay?
niya'om hayza' 'ima bolalasan ki 'ima his'alan ka kayba:en.
english: We have white and blue ones too.
Please give me the clothes in blue.

xsy: kalih kaysa'an So'o rima' rayno'? So'o rima' homayaw ay?
english: kalih, where have you been just now? Did you go exercising?

xsy: 'oka', ya:o rima' tatilhael hi koko' ma'an titibae:iw ka tatimae'.
english: No, I went grocery shopping for my grandma.

xsy: nakhini o, rohaenan So'o honasamez ay? 'am ki yako ma'onhael komSa:o' ay?
english: No wonder! Are you available at night? Would you like to have a meal with me?

xsy: kayni', yako 'am rima' bae:iw ka kayba:en.
english: No, I want to buy some clothes.
Then, I will go with you.

xsy: hini 'aehae' binotoe' ka por'oe' koza' rayhil?
english: Hello, how much is this bunch of vegetables?
The vegetables are $20 for a bunch.
How much are these sweet potatoes?
Sweet potatoes are thirty dollars for a pound.

xsy: be:ay 'iyakin roSa' binotoe' ka por'oe' ki 'aehae' tintin ka 'aewpir.
english: Please give me two bunches of vegetables and a pound of sweet potatoes.

xsy: kalih, yako mangowip ila maraS ka kaka:at, So'o kayzaeh ay paSibae:aeh 'iyakin?
english: kalih, I forgot to bring my pen. Can you lend me one?
I don't have one either. This is 'away's.
Can you lend me the pen for a second? I will return to you immediately.
Thank you and thank 'away for me.

xsy: yako 'am minobih ka hini roSa' kina:at.
english: I want to return these two books.
No problem and what else do you need?

xsy: yako 'am Somibae:aeh hini to:o' ka kina:at.
english: I would like to borrow these three books.

xsy: 'a:ay. to:o' hahila: sizaeh pinobih, 'izi' ngowip o.
english: Sure and remember to return them after three days.
You haven't returned me the eraser.
Then, why is my eraser missing?

xsy: niSo' Si: paSibae:aeh ila hi kalih ay
english: Did you lend it to kalih?

xsy: kiraeh. ya:o ta somingozaw hi siya.
english: I don't know. I will go and ask her.
I will lend you my eraser first.

xsy: 'away, hini katoeh ni kalih pinaSibae:aeh 'iniSo' ay?
english: 'away, did kalih lend you this coat?
No, my mom bought it for me.

xsy: ni kalih ka katoeh hingha' ki 'inSo'o a.
english: kalih 's coat is the same as yours.
His coat is black, so our colors are different.

xsy: 'away, So'o hayza' ay Somibae:aeh ka rayhil kala kalih?
english: 'away, did you borrow money from kalih?

xsy: hayza', ya:o koSa' kaysa'an 'am minobih hi siya, yako mangowip ila maraS ka rayhil.
english: Yes, I was supposed to return to him today, but I forgot to bring the money.
Then, when will you return the money?

xsy: ma'an rim'aen ka pinobih hi siya.
english: I will return to him tomorrow.
Okay, I will tell kalih for you.

xsy: 'aewhaS 'am noka linanger romakep, kaehka: 'am noka talnga' romakep, nakhini 'am kayzaeh.
english: It is correct to catch mice through rangay and catch bamboo partridges through qjiulang.
No wonder! I am mistaken and that's why I cannot catch any of them.

xsy: ya:o tatortoroe' 'iSo'on 'am nak'ino' paskayzaeh ka hini roSa' baseng.
english: Then I will teach you how to set up these two traps.

xsy: 'a:ay! kayzaeh o! nakhini ya:o ma' 'am romakep ila ka 'inalep.
english: Great! I will be able to catch the prey in the future.

xsy: ray pinatiyay ka hinbetel 'a'ibabaw ila, So'o Sa'ila ray saksaka: mari' ka sawki', 'ita' ta'ila ray pinatiyay.
english: The grass in the fields is too tall. Go to the warehouse to take the sickle and let's go to the fields.

xsy: ray takil langi:, So'o kaS'abo' ray saksaka: ma' 'am komita' ila.
english: It is next to the round basket. You will see it when you enter the warehouse.

xsy: 'iya'azem 'am mari', 'izi' patipangih. hiza sawki' soma:om a tomal.
english: Be careful and don't get hurt. The sickle is very sharp.
My trap is under that tree.

xsy: yako hayza' tomiwaSaw rini, 'isa:a' ya:o ra:am ma'an hayno binaseng.
english: I make a mark here, so I know where my trap is.

xsy: hini 'awbo', niya'om 'aSkanen ray lolongan nom pit'aelaw.
english: This is a fish trap which we put beside the river for fishing.

xsy: niya'om hiza 'oka' ka 'awbo', yami noka kapnazip romakep ka 'aelaw.
english: We don't have any fish traps there, so we catch fish with a fishing rod.

xsy: yako 'inokay noka kapnazip pit'aelaw So'o tortoroe' 'iyakin kayzaeh ay?
english: I have never used a fishing rod before, would you mind teaching me next time?
Sure! Let's go fishing together next time.
I will teach you how to make a fish trap next time.

xsy: niSo' kapnazip kakoway ila, nakhara ka:asen ila noka 'aelaw! So'o 'am'amoeh hoehoeh ka kapnazip.
english: Your fishing rod is moving. Isn't the fish on the hook? Pull it up!

xsy: naehan, hini palono' 'aewhay ngilol a tomal. ya:o rini tahoehoeh ka kapnazip, So'o Sa'ila riza mari' ka 'ami' 'iniman.
english: Wait, the ship is rolling heavily. I am here to pull the fishing rod and you should go there to grab me the net.

xsy: So'o hoehoeh ka 'aelaw rini kanman ya:o tatilhaehael 'iSo'on tahoehoeh.
english: Pull the fish to my side and I will help you pull it up.

xsy: tabin o! kaysa'an 'akoy ka minari' kataboe'an ka 'aelaw mayha'ha' ila.
english: Great! It is a bumper crop today with full fish baskets.
Let's go back immediately and share it with everyone.
Stop playing and quickly sit in your seat.

xsy: kaysa'an minay haseb ka Sinangayan, rim'aen maSangay, ta'ila tapanpanra:an!
english: It's Friday today, we have a day off tomorrow. Let's go out and play together!
Great! Let's go to the riverside.
What day will it be tomorrow?

xsy: rim'aen 'ima minay to:o' ka Sinangayan, rim'aen hila:an ta'ila rima' tapakakSiyae' ka mali'!
english: Tomorrow will be Wednesday. Let's go play ball tomorrow afternoon!

xsy: rim'aen ririm'aenan So'o 'am powa' ka kano'?
english: What will you be doing tomorrow morning?

xsy: rim'aen kaSangayan, ya:o 'am ki 'oya' rima' kiyokay.
english: Tomorrow will be Sunday, I will be going to church with my mom.
I feel like vomiting. I need to go to the restroom.

xsy: kamatortoroe', yako biSbiS ka tiyal, 'am rima' kata'owan.
english: Teacher, I have a stomachache. I need to go to the restroom.
May I go wash my hands?
It's almost time for class to end. Wait a little longer.

xsy: kamatortoroe', yako biSbiS a tomalan ka ta'oeloeh, sizaeh ila komsi'ael 'am maSangay.
english: It's almost time for class to end. Wait a little longer.
Okay, take care and go home.

xsy: kamatortoroe', mowa:i' 'aehae' naehan minay 'aehae' ka Sinangayan yako 'am maSangay, yako 'am rima' pakita' ka sinsang.
english: Teacher, I need to take a sick leave next Monday. I have to see a doctor.

xsy: siya biSbiS ka tiyal, siya 'ay kata'owan.
english: She has a stomachache. She's in the restroom.

xsy: kamatortoroe', 'obay biSbiS ka kaSlar, kaysa'an maSangay.
english: Teacher, 'obay has a sore throat. She took a sick leave today.

xsy: yako ta:in a kalih, 'isahini yako lampez tinal'oemaeh ila.
english: My name is ta:in a kalih, and I'm 10 years old.
What ethnic group are you from?
Are all your family members indigenous?
Yes, my whole family is SaySiyat.
No, my father is SaySiyat, and my mother is Hakka.

xsy: hiza 'aehae' mae'iyaeh 'inSo'a yaba' ay? siya piza' ila tinal'oemaeh?
english: Is that your father? How old is he?

xsy: 'ihi', siya 'inmana'a yaba', siya monSayboSi: tinal'oemaeh ila.
english: Yes, he is my father. He is 60 years old.

xsy: 'oka', siya tatini' noka hito' mita', siya monmaykaSpat tinal'oemaeh ila.
english: No, he is an elder of our tribe. He is 80 years old.

xsy: minatini' kamanra:an niSo' piza' ila tinal'oemaeh?
minatini' kamanra:an ma'an lampez o maykaSpat tinal'oemaeh ila.
minatini' kamanra:an niSo' tatini' a tomal ay 'iniSo'?
english: Is your brother much older than you?

xsy: yako 'aehae' kinkaboehoel o moneSpat masa' kin'ibabaw.
honaehnge: ila 'okay kakita', So'o nakhara 'ibabaw ila?
english: I haven't seen you in a while. Have you grown taller?

xsy: 'ihi' a! yako 'aehae' kinkaboehoel o mato:ol masa' kin'ibabaw ila.
yako 'am rima' ray kapatawawan komi:im ka kamatortoroe'.
english: I'm going to the office to see the teacher.
He's going to throw away the trash.
He's at the swimming pool. He's going to compete in a swimming competition later.
Where is tapaS? She's going to compete in a running competition later.

xsy: siya ray kapakba:awan, ya:o taSakobae:aeh hi siya.
english: She's in the auditorium. I'll go call her.
Let's go to the playground together.

xsy: ya:o 'am minSa'la' bae:iw ka kinsi'ael, 'insa'an rima' komi:im 'iSo'on.
english: I'll go buy lunch first, and then I'll meet you later.
Let's carry the lunch boxes together!

xsy: So'o ki:im ka 'aroma', yako 'am rima' komi:im ka kamatortoroe'.
english: You find someone else, I'm going to find the teacher.
No, he's competing in high jump.

xsy: ray ka'a'inola'an ka hahila: So'o 'am 'a'inola' ay?
english: Will you compete in the sports day?

xsy: 'ita' ray ka'a'inola'an ka hahila: 'am powa' ka kano'?
english: What will we do in the sports day?
We will compete in tug of war.

xsy: 'ita' ray ka'a'inola'an ka hahila: 'am tibtibae:iw ka kasi'aelen ay?
english: Will we sell food at the sports day?
Congratulations on getting first place! You're amazing!
Yes, she's sleeping in her room.

xsy: 'oka', baba:aw siya kaSlatar ila, hae:wan ila 'am lobih..
english: No, she's not. She just went out and will be back in the evening.

xsy: siya ray minaypoSal tinaew'an, So'o Sa'ila ki:im hi siya.
english: He's upstairs. You can go up and find him.

xsy: hayza' ay ka mae'iyaeh ray taew'an?
'ataw o, honaehnge: ila 'okay kita' 'iSo'on. So'o kayzaeh ay?
english: It's 'ataw. I haven't seen you in a while! How have you been?

xsy: kayzaeh a! ya:o mowa:i' 'am 'a'iyalatar ki So'o.
english: I'm doing great! I came to chat with you.

xsy: siya ray katalekan homangra: ka tatimae', ya:o takobae:aeh hi siya.
english: He's in the kitchen cooking. Let me go call him.

xsy: siya rima' ray kawnatata:a'an romakep ka tata:a'.
english: She went to the chicken coop to catch chickens.

xsy: nimon baki' 'okik 'ay taew'an, siya ray pinatiyayan, moyo 'ay taew'an 'ayna:a' hi siya.
english: Your grandfather is not at home. He's in the field. Wait for him to come back.
I haven't seen you in a while. You've grown taller.

xsy: komita' So'o mowa:i' yako kin Siyae'.
english: It's so good to see you.
Here's a pineapple for you. Put it in the refrigerator.

xsy: honaehnge: ila 'okay wa:i', ya:o takobae:aeh ka saboeh mowa:i' ma'onhael somi'ael.
english: It's been a while. Let's have a meal together.

xsy: 'izi' ila patawaw, ya:o milkashaw ma' kayzaeh ila, 'ita' ta'a'iyalatar ray kinbaki'an.
english: No need to bother. I'll just have tea. Let's sit in the living room and chat.
Thank you for your hospitality. I have to go now.

xsy: hini tata:a' baba:aw hiwa'en, be:ayen 'iniSo' 'alibihin si'aelen.
english: This chicken was just freshly killed. Take it home and enjoy it slowly.

xsy: 'ita' rim'aen hila:an ta kakita' kayzaeh ay?
english: Can I make an appointment with you tomorrow afternoon?

xsy: 'ita' ta kakita' 'ay kakiSka:atan kayzaeh ay? yami 'am 'omalingo'.
english: How about meeting at school? We need to shoot a video.

xsy: nak'isaza ray kararotonan 'am kayzaeh, yako 'am homiba: 'inoka SaySiyat a kayba:en.
english: Then let's go to the community center. I'll wear folk costume.

xsy: ray niya'om hito' Singil So: minpongaeh kayzaeh a tomalan kita'en. So: minpongaeh ila So'o wa'ila ki:im 'iyakin!
english: The cherry blossoms in our tribe are beautiful when they bloom. Come find me when the flowers bloom!

xsy: nak'isaza 'am mayna:a' tabin ray naba:an, honaehnge: a tomal!
english: That would have to wait until spring. It's too late, isn't it?
Alright! I'm looking forward to it!
May I ask why you decided to move back to the tribe?
I want to return to teach at the local school.
Why not teach in the city?

xsy: yako maSriyae' 'inmana'a hito', ma' 'iyakina matawaw no hito' ma'an.
english: Because I miss my hometown and I also want to give back to the tribe.

xsy: So'o ra:am a tomal tomnon, hiya' tomotoroe' 'iSo'on?
english: You're very skilled at weaving, who taught you?

xsy: koko' ma'an, siya ray niya'om hito' 'ima wa'isan tomnon.
english: It was my grandmother, she is the most skilled weaver in our tribe.
How did you develop an interest in learning weaving?

xsy: tomnon ka kayba:en koSa'en niya'om kaspengan, yako 'iyakina pataSilotor ka kaspengan.
english: Weaving is a part of our culture, and I want to ensure its continuity.

xsy: So'o wa'isan, hini 'am honaehnge: ay 'am poSak?
english: You're really talented. Does it take a long time to make?

xsy: 'oka', 'aehae' ka Sinangayan ma' kayzaeh ila. ho'ol pilwaha:anen, 'isa:a' pa'oSa'en ka tatamol 'ilo'en, 'isa:a' kayzaeh ila 'aSkanen ray totowih 'izo'.
english: No, it only takes about a week. After steaming the sticky rice and white rice, we mix it with yeast powder, and then it can be stored in a jar.

xsy: ma'an hini hayza' ka silih ki 'oe'oeng, saboeh yako nonak pinamowa' o!
english: I have chili and lokiy, both grown by myself!

xsy: yako minowa' ka hini kayba:en, 'am koza' rayhil?
english: I like this piece of clothing. How much is it?

xsy: wa'isan a tomalan, waelae' sowiti' kayzaeh ay?
english: It's too expensive. Can't you lower the price a bit?
No, if I lower it further, I'll lose money.
Alright then, I'll take a black piece of clothing.

xsy: yako 'am bae:iw hini ka malat ki hini koloban.
english: I want this knife and this pot.

xsy: saboeh 'am roSa' siyaen rayhil, hini yako nonak pinaskayzaeh.
english: It's a total of 2000 dollars. I handmade these, and they are guaranteed to last a long time.

xsy: yako komobae:aeh ka kapa'onhaelan mowa:i' bae:iw, kayzaeh ay waelae' naehan?
english: I'll introduce my friend to buy. Can you give a further discount?
Alright! I'll give you a 20% discount.

xsy: wa'ila kita' o! hayza' ka kayba:en ki tatpo' katibae:iwen.
english: Come and take a look! We sell clothes and hats.

xsy: kayba:en so'hae' to:o' o monaseb rayhil, to:o' ka kayba:en 'am 'aehae' siyaen rayhil.
english: One piece of clothing is 350 dollars, three pieces for 1000 dollars.

xsy: yako bae:iw so'hae' nanaw, be:ay 'iyakin 'ima SaSo'.
english: I'll just buy one piece, please give me a new one.

xsy: So'o kayzaeh, yako 'iyakina bae:iw ka Sinpaehpae: ki mae'aew 'ayam.
english: Hello, I would like to buy sticky rice and braised pork with maqaw pepper.

xsy: Sinpaehpae: Sitil'amet ila. yako hayza' naehan ka tani' piyang, So'o 'am bae:iw ay?
english: The rice is sold out. I have tana pancakes, would you like to buy them?

xsy: 'a:ay, be:ay so'hae' 'iniman, yako rim'aen ila mowa:i' bae:iw ka Sinpaehpae:.
english: Alright, please give me one. I'll come back next time to buy rice.

xsy: 'a:ay, ya:o noka bilas potoyon 'iniSo', nakhini monaseb rayhil.
english: Okay, I'll pack it in a bag for you. That'll be 50 dollars.

xsy: yaba' kakhayza'an 'inokay kiSka:at ray 'oes'oeso'an nanaw, ray taew'an patiyay, 'aewhay ka kin'i'iyaeh, rengreng nonak 'omahiwis Sa' 'okik Sekla' ka kina:at"
english: So: komita' ka kina:at ta'oeloeh ma' malwelwel

xsy: yako kaysa'an hinSayboSi: o 'aehae' potngor ray kakiSka:atan.
english: I arrived at school at seven today.

xsy: kiSka:at ila kamatortoroe' kaS'abo' ray kakiSka:atan kamatilhael Sa' "'in'itol! te'en!"
english: It's time for class, the teacher walked into the classroom, and the monitor said: "Stand up! Salute!"

xsy: ray 'am kiSka:at, kamatortoroe' tomotoroe' 'iniya'om nom Sempe: kapayaka:i'.
english: In class, the teacher taught us the SaySiyat language of numbers.

xsy: yami tani kamatortoroe' kiSka:at, yami ma:tol ila nom Sempe: kapa:tol.
english: We followed the teacher to read, we sang the number song.
I have learned many SaySiyat languages.

xsy: ya:o sa'sa'ih ka hahila: rima' kiSka:at, ya:o sa'sa'ih ka hahila: tatoroe' ka kapayaka:i' ya:o 'am manabih pakbaezae' hi 'oya'.
english: I go to school every day, I learn the SaySiyat language every day, and I want to tell my mother.

xsy: ni yaba' ma'an raro:o' hi kalih.
ya:o hayza' 'aehae' minatini' kamamanra:an siya Sin ta:inin, siya 'isahini lampez o 'aehae' tinal'oemaeh.
english: I have a brother, his name is ta:in, he is 11 years old.
We study in the same school.

xsy: yako ki minatini' kamamannra:an minowa' ma:tol.
english: Both my brother and I like to sing.

xsy: ya:o minowa' lalangoy, ray minaSangay, yami 'aehae' taew'an ma'onhael rima' lalangoy.
english: I like swimming. During the holidays, our whole family go swimming together.

xsy: ya:o minowa' Sekla' ka 'ima SaSo' kapa'onhaelan yami kayzaeh ma'onhael ma:tol ki lalangoy.
english: I love meeting new people, we can sing and swim together.
There are five people in our family.
There are three brothers and sisters in our family.

xsy: ya:o ki yaba', 'oya' minatini' kamamanra:an ki minatini' minkoringan ma'onhael rowaSek.
english: I live with my father, mother, brother and sister.
My father is tall and he is a policeman.
My mother is thin and my mom is a doctor.

xsy: yaba' ray taew'an ki yami malnoSaySiyat.
english: My father speaks the ethnic language with us at home.

xsy: yami ray haba:an 'ima 'inaro' kaSangayan hahila: lobih ray 'asang.
english: We will all go back to the tribe during the summer vacation.

xsy: yako kila minatini ma'onhael rima' romakep ka takem.
english: My brothers and sisters and I will catch frogs together.
I like our family very much.
I went out with my mother today.

xsy: 'ima Sera: kawaS kinhis'alan, kawaS 'okik kaskes ma' 'okik rikrika:, ba:i' kin'iya'zaw.
english: The sky is blue during the day, the weather is neither cold nor hot, and the wind is cool.

xsy: yami ray hinhinbetelan maSa:eng somi'ael ka pang, basang hila:en noka hahila:, koza' kinha:olhoel.
english: We ate bread on the grass, the sun was shining on us, and it was very warm.
In the afternoon, the sky turned red.
I asked my mother why the sky is red.
Mom said, maybe the typhoon is coming.

xsy: hae:wan ray kawaS 'oka' ka homom, bintoe'an kas'oehaez ila.
english: There were no clouds in the sky at night, and the stars came out.

xsy: ray karara:an, ya:o paho'alo' ka bintoe'an.
english: On the way home, I made a wish with the stars
I hope the typhoon doesn't come, I still want to go out to play again.

xsy: ma'an kakiSka:atan ray 'in niya'om a taew'an langi:, ya:o sa'sa'ih ka hahila: manra:an rima' ray kakiSka:atan, ma' manra:an lobih ray taew'an.
english: My school is next to our house, I walk to school every day, and I also walk home.

xsy: niya'om kakiSka:atan 'okik sobae:oeh, 'okik 'akoey ka kamakiSka:at, SaSekla' hahi:il.
english: Our school is not big, there are not many students, everyone knows each other.

xsy: Saeboeh korkoring raroton ray kap'ae'ae:iwan, ma'onhael makakSiyae' ki 'a'iyalatar.
english: All the children will gather in the playground, play ball and chat together.

xsy: lakamatortoroe' ma' mae'onhael ki yami makakSiyae', kakiSka:atan nak 'aehae' taew'an.
english: The teachers also play with us, the school is one big family.

xsy: sa'sa'ih ka hahila: somaepoh, 'ita' 'am 'okay pakhara:i' katatoroe'an.
english: We have to clean every day, and everyone has to clean the classroom.

xsy: hayza' mae'iyaeh tomi:iS ka hinohaez, hayza' mae'iyaeh somaepoh ka rape:.
english: Some people clean the windows, some sweep the floor.

xsy: yami ma' ra:am somaepoeh ray kakiSka:atan kalihokan, 'ita' 'a'apel kapatawawen, kakiSka:atan sa'sa'ih ka hahila: ma' 'am 'okik hara:i'.
english: We will also clean every corner of the school. Everyone works together, and the school is very clean every day.

xsy: kahiya', yako rima' ray 'asang payrarongaw hi baki'.
english: Yesterday, I went to visit my grandpa in the tribe.

xsy: yami honaehnge: ila 'okik kakita', yako maSriyae' hi siya.
english: We haven't seen each other for a long time and I miss him a lot.

xsy: baki' komita' 'iyakin, pasi'ael ka ba:ay o parae'oe: ka kashaw 'iyakin.
english: As soon as grandpa saw me, he invited me to eat watermelon and drink tea.

xsy: ni baki' pinamowa' ka ba:ay 'anhil, sa'owaz kayzaeh a tomal si'aelen.
english: The watermelon grown by grandpa is very sweet and really delicious.

xsy: yako ma' minowa' ni baki' ka kashaw, kayzaeh rae'oe:on.
english: I also like grandpa's tea, it's tasted good too.

xsy: ray 'ima hila:an, yako ki koko' ma'onhael tikinsi'ael.
english: At noon, I cooked lunch with my grandma.

xsy: ni koko tinalek 'akoey a ta:an, hayza' ka 'aelaw, hayza' ka tata:a', hayza' ka lilom, hayza' ka mona:.
english: Grandma cooked a big lunch, including fish, chicken, pumpkin, and snails.

xsy: komsi'ael sizaeh, yami rima' ray tatimae'an titatimae'.
english: After lunch, we went to the vegetable garden to pick vegetables.

xsy: koko' mari' 'akoey ka 'aewpir, rokol ki 'oe'ong, Sipa'alibih 'iyakin ray taew'an.
english: Grandma brought me a lot of sweet potatoes, taro and buckwheat, and asked me to take them home.

xsy: yako ki lasiya papil'awan ila, So: honasamez ila 'am mowa:i' naehan komita' hi lasiya.
english: I said goodbye to them and said I'd see them next time.

xsy: kaysa'an kamatortoroe' maraS 'iniya'om, rima' ray kita'an ka Sinpanan yami ray kakaS'abo'an 'aehae' 'aehae' wawa:ih bae:iw nom kaS'abo' ka pinaSkira:a'.
english: Today the teacher took us to the zoo, and we lined up at the gate to buy tickets.

xsy: kaS'abo' ray kakita'an ka Sinpanan, kamatortoroe' manabih Sa', "ray kati'aela' ka kita'an ka kabkabaeha:, hikor kakita'an ka Siba:i', 'ita' 'iSkanonak kita' ila."
english: After entering the zoo, the teacher said, There are birds in the front and snakes in the back

xsy: yako tikot ka Siba:i', isa:a kayni' komita' ka Siba:i'.
english: I'm afraid of snakes, so I don't look at snakes.

xsy: yako komita' 'akoy ka kabkabaeha:, lasiya ray kaehoy babaw homayhayap, hayza' naehan Saehoro: ka kal'oe' ray kaehoy horo' 'izo' minae'rem.
english: I saw a lot of birds flying around in the trees and saw owls sleeping in tree hollows.

xsy: ray kakita'an ka Sinpanan hayza' ka ba:ong, hanowan ki heklaw, ma'an kakhayza'an 'inokay Saehoro: i' hini Sipanan, kaysa'an kita'en ila hahi:il kinSiyae' a tomal.
english: There are elephants, horses and tigers in the zoo. I have never seen these animals before. I was really happy to see them today.
I took a lot of pictures and showed them to my parents.

xsy: mayhal 'am ki yaba' 'oya' ma'onhael 'am mowa:i' naehan rini.
english: Next time I will come with my parents.

xsy: ray hini minaSangay hahila: yako ki minatini' minkoringan rima' taytong payrarongaw hi mama'.
english: This holiday, my sister and I went to Taitung to visit my uncle.

xsy: yami 'in'alay taypae' papama' ka kalihaepoyan rima' taytong.
english: We took the train from Taipei to Taitung.

xsy: potngor ray taytong, mama' seme:ez kapapama'an mowa:i' ray ka'ayna:an kapapama'an sasbong 'iniya'om.
english: When we arrived in Taitung, my uncle drove to the station to pick us up.

xsy: ka'ayna:an kapapama'an 'al'alihan kala mama' ray taew'an, papama' honha:i' ma' potngor.
english: The station is not far from my uncle's house, and it's just a short drive away.

xsy: ni mama' taew'an langi: hayza' 'aehae' 'ima mowahil kaSpanan ka Sinpanan, yami' papama' ka ritinSiya' rima' ray kaSpanan ka Sinpanan.
english: There is a big ranch near my uncle's house, and we rode bicycles to the ranch together.

xsy: ray kaSpanan ka Sinpanan, yami tomabo: ka Siri' papama' ka hanowan.
english: In the ranch, my uncle took us to feed the sheep and ride horses.

xsy: roehaenan, yami mae'onhael rima' ray titiyaman komSa:o'.
english: In the evening, we went to the city to have dinner together.

xsy: rima' ray titiyaman 'asang 'akoy ka kapapama'an, 'isa:a yami papama' ka 'otobay rima' risaza.
english: There are a lot of cars in the city, so we go there by motorcycle.

xsy: 'am lobih ila, kita'en 'otobay Sikarma' ila, 'isa:a yami' papama' ka baSe' lobih.
english: When we were about to leave, we found that the motorcycle had been stolen, so we had to leave by bus.

xsy: 'isa:a hini yami lobih ila ray taypae', 'okik ra:am ni mama' 'otobay tihoro:on ila ay.
english: Now that we are back in Taipei, I don't know if my uncle's motorcycle has been found.

xsy: ray 'ima 'ol'olae'an niya'om taew'an ray walo', kiSka:at ila, ba:aw ila ray to'ing, 'isa:a ray raehoran ila nanaw rowa:Sek.
english: When we were young, our family lived in Donghe. After I started school, we moved to Taoyuan and have been living in the city ever since.

xsy: kiSka:at ila ray kam'ibabaw kakiSka:atan, yako pawhi:il ila 'aehae' kakiSka:aten noka SinSinraeho' kaspengan. Sekla' ila ray taywan SinSinraeho' hayza' 'akoy ka 'ima 'okik hingha' ka kaspengan.
english: After I went to college, I took a course on aboriginal culture and learned that the aboriginal people in Taiwan have various and rich cultures.

xsy: 'isa:a, 'isahini tinal'omaeh ray 'ima 'inaro' ka kaSangayan, yako ki minatini' kamamanra:an lobih ray 'asang somingozaw ka tatini', 'am Sekla' ka 'in nonak a kaspengan.
english: So this summer, my brother and I went back to our tribe to visit the elderly, hoping to understand the culture of our own ethnic group.

xsy: tatini' monmaykaSpat ila tinal'omaeh, ma' kita'en nak 'al'alak naehan.
english: The old man is already eighty years old, but he still looks like a middle-aged man.

xsy: ya:o somingzaw hi siya ra:am piza' kapayaka:i', siya malnoSySiyat ra:am a tomal, ma' ra:am 'oyaeh malnoSaypapa:aS, malnomoto: ki malnoripon.
english: I asked him which languages he knew, and he was fluent in Saisiyat, as well as Atayal, Hakka and Japanese.

xsy: yako somingozaw hi siya 'isa:a ra:am ila, siya 'ima 'ol'olae'an kiSka:at ka 'alnoripon, minkoringan nisiya Saypapa:aS, siya ray kapatawawan Sekla' 'akoy ka moto:, 'isa:a siya ra:am 'akoy ka kapayaka:i'.
english: I asked him to find out that he learned Japanese when he was a child, his wife is an Atayal, and he knows many Hakkas at work, so he can speak so many languages.

xsy: yami 'ima somingozaw, tatini' manabih 'akoy nisiya kinra:aman nom 'omalep ka howaw.
english: During our interview, the old man talked about a lot of traditional knowledge about hunting.

xsy: 'ana yami haSa' baezae', niya'om noka laleke: 'alingo'on, 'isa:a kayzaeh hayza' naehan kabaezae'en.
english: Although we could't fully understand it, we could record it on our cell phones and listen to it more.

xsy: 'ima 'ol'olae'an 'okik Sekla' ka 'in nonak a kaspengan, komita' nonak ma' SaySiyat kaSikar a tomal.
english: When I was young, I didn't understand the culture of my ethnic group, and I was a little embarrassed that I was an aborigine.

xsy: Sekla' kin'akoy, nonak Sapang SaySiyat, sa'owaz maynonak a tomal, ma' kayzaeh patopa: ma'an Sapang ka Sinrahoe'.
english: The more I know, the more I feel that being a Saisiyat is unique and something to be proud of.

xsy: 'isa'an rohaenan, minayti' kamanra:an 'am lobih ray taew'an.
english: My younger brother is going home this evening.

xsy: yako ki koko rima' ray ka titibae:iwan ka tatima' bae:iw ka tata:a'.
english: My grandma and I went to the market to buy chickens and prepared a delicious dinner for my younger brother.

xsy: yami maray ka titibae:iwan ka tatimae', tinitibae:iw 'akoy baba:aw minari' ka por'oe'.
english: We passed the vegetable stand, which had a lot of fresh green vegetables.

xsy: yami bae:iw ka por'oe', Sako: ki sitaew.
english: We bought water spinach, yams and carrots.

xsy: ray langi: kamatitibae:iw ka boway tahoki' Sa', "ma'an panrang ki 'a:immapizos 'anhih, o bae:iw sowiti' ay!"
english: The owner of the nearby fruit stand said: "My pineapples and peaches are very sweet. Buy some!"

xsy: yami bae:iw ila ka panrang ki 'a:imapizos.
yami maray kamatitibae:iw ka 'ayam, tahoki' Sa', "So'o 'am bae:iw ka kano? kaysa'an tata:a' sopaloy o kerpe:, 'aehae' to:o' kaeboehoel rayhil."
english: We passed the meat stall, and the boss said, "What do you want to buy? Today's chickens are big and fat, and one is 300 NTD."

xsy: koko komoSa' wa'isan tomal, somingozaw hi tahoki' kayzaeh ay waelae' sowiti' ka rayhil.
english: Grandma thought it was too expensive and asked the boss if it could be cheaper.

xsy: tahoki' Sa' hororay a tomal, 'amkay waelae' ila.
english: But the boss said that it is already very cheap and cannot be reduced any further.

xsy: ray kabih tahoki' Sa', wa'ila bae:iw ma'an ka 'aelaw, ma'an 'aelaw rarahoe' o hororay.
english: The boss next door said, come and buy my fish, my fish is big and cheap.

xsy: bi:il ila yami bae:iw ila ka tata:a' ma' bae:iw ka 'aelaw 'alibihin ray taew'an taleken, tinalek 'aehae' talka: ka tatimae'.
english: In the end we bought chicken and fish, and went home to cook a table of food.
After waiting for a long time, it was already dark.

xsy: minayti' kamamanra:an pawa:i' ka laleke: manabih Sa', hitay hayza' ka howaw kayni SiSangay, 'am 'aehae' naehan ka Sinangayan ray kaSangayan hahila: 'am lobih ila.
english: The younger brother called back and said that the army suddenly couldn't take a vacation and would not be back until the next Sunday.

xsy: koko Sa' tinalek kin'akoy, kobae:oeh ka saeboeh wa'ila si'ael!
english: Grandma said that she has cooked so much, so let's eat together!

xsy: yami pawa:i' ka 'aeh'aehael, ma'onhael mowa:i' komSa:o' ka 'ima kayzaeh kasi'aelen.
english: We invited friends and family to have a great dinner together.

xsy: ya:o hayza' 'aehae' kapa'ohhaelan Sin kalihin, siya rengreng mangowip maraS ka kakrang'an.
english: I have a classmate named kalih, he often forgets to bring things.

xsy: 'am kiSka:at ila, siya Somibae:aeh kala kapa'onhan ka kaka:at, tati:iS 'oka' ma' kaka:atan ka kina:at.
english: During class, he borrowed pencils, erasers or notebooks from his classmates.

xsy: monhael, monpoSal, monto:o' saeboeh ma' paSibae:aeh hi siya.
english: Once, twice, three times, everyone would lend him something.

xsy: 'ana nakhini, siya hayza' 'ima 'awhay ka pinatawaw, rengreng Somibae:aeh 'okay pinobih ka kakrangi'an.
english: But he has a bad habit of often borrowing things but not returning them.

xsy: bi:il ila saeboeh mae'iyaeh ma' kayni' ila paSibae:aeh hi siya ka kakrangi'an.
english: In the end, no one wanted to borrow anything from him.

xsy: hayza' 'aehae' hahila:, yami saeboeh rima' manmanra:an.
english: One day, we all went on an outing together.

xsy: ray ra:an, kalih 'iniya 'inoSa' ray kata'owan, siya 'okay 'araS nom tomi:iS ka zinowas.
english: On the way, kalihwanted to go to the bathroom, but he forgot to bring toilet paper.

xsy: siya Somina' ka kapa'onhaelan, saeboeh ma' tiSkobae:oeh Sa', ya:o ma' 'okay 'araS o.
english: He borrowed toilet paper from his classmates, but everyone told him that I didn't bring them either.

xsy: kalih 'isa:a homangih ila, siya bi'i: komoSa' 'ampowa' moyo saeboeh kayni' paSibae:aeh 'iyakin nom tomi:iS ka zinowas!
english: kalih burst into tears. He said angrily, why don't everyone lend me toilet paper!

xsy: kapa'onhaelan nisiya' mayaka:i' hi siya, ma' So'o nonak 'okay 'araS o, So: paSibaehen ka kakrangi'an So'o ma' haSa' minobih!
english: The classmate told him, because you didn't bring it yourself, and you wouldn't return the things lent to you!

xsy: mowa:i' 'aehae' hahila: kiSka:at, kalih minremreme' potngor ila ray kakiSka:atan, kalih mari' ka Sinibae:aehan ka kakrangi'an Sipinobih saeboeh ka kapa'onhaelan.
english: The next day at school, kalih arrived at school early and returned everything he had borrowed from his classmates.

xsy: kalih tiSkobih ila ka kapa'onhaelan, mayaka:i' Sa' mowa:i' naehan siya nonak 'am maraS ila ka kakrangi'an, ma' ma'alo' kapa'onhaelan Somiwa' paSibae:aeh hi siya ka kakrang'an.
english: kalih apologized to the students and said that he would definitely bring his own things in the future, and thanked the classmates for their willingness to lend him things before.
My dad is a hunter of the tribe.

xsy: yako ray 'ima 'ol'olae'an, yaba' ki mama' ray 'ima rohaenan rima' 'omalep, maraS ka sibal ki wawatos.
english: When I was little, my dad and uncle would go out at night with hunting knives and guns.

xsy: 'ima Sera: ila, lasiya' malibih ka 'inalep kakrangi'an lobih ray taew'an.
english: At daybreak, they returned with their prey.

xsy: mak'aehae' ma' waliSan, mak'aehae' ma' hapis, 'oka' ma' kaehka:.
english: Sometimes it was a boar, sometimes a flying squirrel, and occasionally a pheasant.
They would divide the prey at the entrance of the village and share it with the tribe.

xsy: yako rengreng 'omaybel hi yaba', 'am taniSowaw hi yaba' rima' 'omalep.
english: Every time I quarreled with my father, I wanted to go hunting with my father.

xsy: yaba' Sa' So: ya:o 'ibabaw ila, siya 'am maraS ila 'iyakin.
english: Dad said that he would take me with me when I grew up.

xsy: ray 'asang kamanra:an noka baseng romakep ka kakrangi'an, lasiya ma' ra:am Sitalnga' ki linanger maSkan ka binaseng.
english: The men of the tribe also trap their prey, making lasso traps and rock traps.

xsy: ma'an yaba' ra:am pakkayzaeh ka talnga', yaba' mayaka:i' Sa', hini nom romakep ka kaehka:, 'ita' pakkayzaeh kita' noka ka'alepen ka Sinarakan, baseng 'aSkan ray kapayziza'an nasiya'.
english: My dad is very good at making lasso traps. Dad said that this is used to catch pheasants. We have to carefully observe the footprints of the prey, and the traps should be placed on the path of the prey.

xsy: 'am 'omam'amoeh ma'onhael kil tatini' rima' 'omalep, yako sa'sa'ih ka hahila: lomoehloehay paskayzaeh nom baseng, kin'alikaeh ma'an 'inaSkan ka baseng, pateleng ila ka 'inalep.
english: In order to go hunting with adults as soon as possible, I practiced making traps every day, and soon my traps can really catch prey.

xsy: yaba' komita' manabih 'iyakin, mayhael So'o 'am 'ima wa'isan kama'alep.
english: Dad saw it and told me that I will be a very good hunter in the future.

xsy: 'isahini yako 'ibabaw ila, ya:o pama' ka boehoe: ki siwa:, tani hi yaba' rima' 'omalep.
english: Now that I have grown up, I carry my bow and arrows and go hunting with my father.
When returning to the village, share the hunted prey with the tribe.

xsy: yaba' Sa', ma'alo' a tomal noka tatini' ka hino'alo', mobe:ay 'ini mita' kin'akoey ka 'inalep.
english: Dad said, we want to thank the ancestors for their blessings, so that we have a lot of prey to harvest.

xsy: yako karim'aenan rima' ray kakiSka:atan papahowih ila.
english: I was late for school this morning.

xsy: rima' ray kakiSka:atan, yako mangowip maraS ka kabang.
english: When I was going to school, I forgot to bring my backpack.
I didn't bring anything with me.

xsy: ray 'am kiSka:at, yako ki kapa'onhaelan ma'onhael komita' ka kina:at.
english: During class, I and my classmates read the textbook together.

xsy: 'am 'a'inola', kapa'onhaelan paSibae:aeh 'iyakin ka kaka:at ki tati:iS.
english: During the exam, a classmate lent me a pen and an eraser.

xsy: kamatortoroe' manabih 'iyakin komoSa', "mowa:i' nahan 'inremreme' 'in'itol, 'izi' papahowih ila!"
english: The teacher told me, Wake up earlier next time and don't be late again!""

xsy: ma'an kapa'onhaelan Sin ta:in, siya ma' 'anka SaySiyat a korkoring.
english: My good friend's name is ta:in, and he is also an SaySiyat child.
We study together in the Sawi' tribe.

xsy: yami rengreng ma'onhael bazae' noka tatini' Sipayaka:i' ka kinbazae'an, yami ra:am a tomal malnoSaySiyat.
english: We often listen to the elders telling stories together, and we both can speak the SaySiyat proficiently.

xsy: yako 'ibabaw ma' kerpe:, ta:in 'irira:i'an ma' bali'.
english: I am tall and overweight, while ta:in is short and thin.

xsy: ta:in wa'isan, saeboeh ma' minowa' hi siya.
english: ta:in is very energetic, and everyone likes him a lot.

xsy: kaysa'an ray kakiSka:atan 'am homayaw ka basang, ray kakiSka:atan 'akoey ka pinatawaw ka'a'inola'en.
english: Today was the school's sports day, and the school organized many competitions.

xsy: hayza' rara:hoeh ka Sina:iS, tomako: ka mali', 'ae'ae:aew, homlal ki mae'nae' ka boehoe:.
english: There were tug of war, soccer, running, dancing, and archery.
I participated in the running competition.

xsy: yako mam 'ae'ae:aew, yako ngizo' ila, poe'oe' ma'an ramoramo'an ila.
english: When I was running, I fell down, and my knees were bleeding.

xsy: 'ana nakhini ya:o ma' min'itol naehan, 'okay patae'aes 'am 'ae'ae:aew.
english: But I stood up and continued running forward.

xsy: yako talsekel ila, saeboeh mae'iyaeh ma' kin Siyae'.
english: Everyone was happy when I reached the finish line.

xsy: 'ana 'okay mari' ka minay 'aehae' Sinepe:, yako ma' kin Siyae', yako hayza' paksizaeh 'am 'a'inola.
english: Although I didn't get first place, I'm glad because I completed the race.

xsy: kahiya' yako ki yaba rima' payrarongaw hi mama' ma'an.
english: Yesterday, my father and I visited my uncle.

xsy: siya mayaka:i' 'iniya'om, ray taew'an sinakeban maehtang ila.
english: He told us that there was a hole in the roof of his house.

xsy: siya 'am tal'izaeh ka sinakeban, 'inray sinakeban Saehae' ila.
english: He fell off the roof while repairing it.

xsy: yaba' maraS ka katin 'ayam ki pinlong 'ini mama'.
english: My father brought beef and betel nuts for my uncle.

xsy: yako ki mama' ray pino'azis 'a'iyalatar, siya paSekla' 'akoey ka kinbazae'an.
english: My uncle and I chatted in the room, and he shared many stories.

xsy: yako 'am rasiwazay ila, mama' romokor 'iyakin komoSa' So'o 'ibabaw ila, ma' tomal a tomal ila.
english: Before I left, my uncle praised me for growing taller and becoming more handsome.

xsy: yako Sa:, "So: mama' 'ae'ay, kayzaeh ila 'isa:a' wa:i' ila panpanra:an kanniya'om ray taew'an."
english: I said, When your foot gets better

xsy: ray roSa' siyan Sam'iyaeh o roSa' tinal'oemaeh, to'oya' 'a'iyalahoe: noka SaSinSinrahoe' pinaSkira:a' ka raro:o' kayzaeh ka:aten nanaw 'anoka SaySiyat a raro:o'.
english: In 2022, the government announced that indigenous identification cards can include tribal names separately.

xsy: yako somingozaw 'ima honaehnge: ila kamarima' homa:ih ka to'oya' ray pinaSkira:a' ka raro:o' "patnonak noka SaySiyat a raro:o'" Say hito' 'al'alak hi taro'.
english: I interviewed taro', a young tribal member who has long been advocating for the inclusion of tribal names on identification cards.

xsy: yako ki siya hayza' ka pinapoe'oe' ray hini 'aehae' kaSangayan 'am rima' kansiya ray taew'an somingozaw hi siya.
english: We had arranged to visit his home this holiday for the interview.

xsy: ray 'am somingozaw, siya pakSekla' ila 'iyakin nisiya raro:o' 'inay'ino', ma' pakSekla' lasiya 'aehae' taew'an mae'iyaeh ki 'insiya'a hito'.
english: During the interview, he introduced to me the origin of his name and also introduced me to his family and tribe.

xsy: yako somingozaw hi siya 'ampowa' somapih ka raro:o', 'ima tatini' pinaSkira:a' 'aewhay ay?
english: I asked him why he insisted on changing his name. Wasn't the old registration method sufficient?

xsy: siya tiSkobae:oeh 'iyakin komSa', tani to'oya' kina:at 'am 'okay Sekla' i' Sapang raro:o' nisiya, ma' hayza' mae'iyaeh Somin hi siya "ta-Siyan-Sen" 'isa:a ma' 'akoey 'ima pakaysawa'en ka howaw.
english: He told me that using Chinese characters could not accurately convey his name, and others would still call him \Da Xian Sheng

xsy: taro' Sa, "tani noka SinSinrahoe' kina:at ka raro:o' Sapang 'inmita'a raro:o'. ma'an raro:o' mina 'iwan niya'om Sinrahoe', niya'om 'aehae' taew'an, niya'om pinaSkira:a' pakSiwa' haeba:an SinSinrahoe' nonak tomihoroe: ka 'in nonak a raro:o'."
english: taro' said, \The names written in indigenous languages are our true names. My name represents our ethnic group

xsy: kahiya' yako tani hi koko' rima' ray ka titibae:iwan, titibae:iw ka tatimae', koko' maraS 'akoey nisiya nonak pinamowa' ka por'oe', ma' paskayzaeh 'anoka SinSinrahoe' a kasi'aelen no saeboeh.
english: Yesterday, I went to the market with my grandmother to set up a stall. My grandmother brought a lot of vegetables that she grew herself and also prepared indigenous cuisine for everyone.

xsy: lasiya saeboeh minowa' ni koko' ka tinitibae:iw, baehko' ki 'anhi' haeba:an mae'iyaeh bae:iw, haeba:an mae'iyaeh mowa:i' Santalam nisiya ka tinalek.
english: Everyone loved my grandmother's stall. Many people bought the chilis and African eggplants, and many people came to taste the dishes she cooked.

xsy: nisiya tinalek ka baehko' ki ho'ol kayzaeh a tomal si'aelen, hayza' naehan noka ma'aew rinenge: waliSan 'ayam, haeba:an mae'iyaeh minowa', haeba:an mae'iyaeh mowa:i' kanniya'om ray ka titibae:iwan mayna:a'.
english: The ferns and sticky rice she cooked were delicious, as well as the braised pork with maqaw pepper and wild boar meat. The flavors attracted many customers, and everyone lined up at our stall.

xsy: koko' mam tomalek, yako ray langi: mam kamae:oeh ka mae'iyaeh, yako ray kabih 'omo'oe: Sa, "por'oe' nonak pinamowa' o, 'inokay po'iyo'i o, 'am'amoeh wa'ila' bae:iw o!"
english: While my grandmother was cooking, I was on the side attracting customers. I shouted, \The vegetables are self-grown

xsy: niya'om 'inaraS karangi'an honha:i' nanaw Sitil'aemet ila, koko' Sa, "ma' hayza' 'iSo'on mowa:i' tatilhaehael la."
english: Our goods sold out quickly, and my grandmother said, \It's all thanks to your help.\""

xsy: hini pinatawaw, ya:o ma' tatoroe' ila noka SinSinrahoe' 'inay 'os'oso'an pinamowa'an ki kasi'aelen ka kinra:aman, ma' ra:am ila mowa:i' titibae:iw ka karangi'an hopay mina.
english: Through this event, I learned about indigenous plants and food and experienced the hard work of running a stall.

xsy: komita' ni koko' kinminowa'an tani 'anka kakhayza'an a kasi'aelen, yako mina patopa: a tomal.
english: Seeing my grandmother's passion for traditional food, I feel very proud and honored.
